text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%0a!Front rounded vowels Comparing English and Mandarin%0a%0a:Author: angelaw%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aEnglish does not have a front rounded vowel%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aFront rounded vowels are vowels articulated with the tongue positioned forward in the mouth and rounded lips. On WALS, these vowels are categorized as high or mid meaning the tongue height can either be high and close to the roof of the mouth or mid around the center. The majority of languages displayed on the map do not use any front rounded vowels, but there are certainly some which do have these vowels and many of these are quite widely spoken.%0a%0aThe English language does not contain any front rounded vowels, but Mandarin contains high front rounded vowels. In English, all front vowels are unrounded. However, in mandarin there is the vowel [ü] where the highest point of the tongue is close to the front of the mouth and the lips are rounded and bunched together. %0a%0aI actually speak both English and Mandarin and so I found this fact particularly interesting. My mom’s name actually has this particular vowel in it and so it’s always quite a process teaching American English speakers how to pronounce her name. This has happened so consistently to the point where she has adopted an unofficial English name that would make it easier for American English speakers to address her. From this example, I think that there’s definitely a possibility that factors such as a vowel not existing in one language can create potential barriers between people. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://wals.info/languoid/lect/wals_code_mnd%0ahttps://phoible.org/inventories/view/1047#tipa%0ahttps://phoible.org/inventories/view/160#tipa%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210227-175626-842960#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Why English Speakers struggle to produce front rounded vowels %0a-> - sebastiang%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThis expansion deals with how the feature value (front rounded vowels) presents a special challenge to speech synthesis.%0a%0aIn most languages, front vowels are usually unrounded while back and mid/high vowels are usually rounded. This is because lip rounding reinforces the "low pitched acoustic overtones that are characteristic of back and non-low vowels. Specifically, rounding and protruding the lips lowers the frequencies produced by the glottal source in the oral tract. This adds to the lowering effect caused by moving the tongue body back.%0a%0aThe fact that we associate back and non-low vowels with roundness and front high vowels with unroundness may be the reason why American English speakers find it difficult to produce rounded front vowels. Languages such as Mandarin which are more flexible with rounding have greater variety in vowel production. %0a%0ahttps://wals.info/chapter/11%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210227-175626-842960#%0a#foxbegin 210227-210010-317700#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!difficulty in pronouncing foreign names %0a-> - kyuwonW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI also have a similar experience in having many American English speakers be confused with the correct pronunciation of my name. Being tired of people asking repetitively what my name is wherever I went, I got myself an English name at first. But I really didn't like this because every time I told people my English name, it felt like I was giving a fake name, like when ordering coffee from Starbucks. Therefore, I found a simple way of explaining my real name with letters that are used by English speakers, which is saying "Kyuwon = q1". By converting my name into an alphabet and a number, now I can just easily introduce my name to anyone and didn't have to use the English name. %0a%0aName constitutes of one's identity, so repetitively mispronouncing one's name may seem rude. But it is definitely hard for people to pronounce sounds that aren't in their native language, like the front rounded vowel ü. These technical differences in language do create barriers between people even though they are speaking the same language. It would actually be hard to narrow this technical gap. However, with increasing awareness of diversity every day, people are more willing to accept diverse dialects, tones, and pronunciations without stereotypes. Now in universities, workplaces, and social groups, people attempt to pronounce each other's names correctly until success. These efforts of respecting diversity and each other's language would be a way to solve problems occurring from these barriers. %0a%0aThe below link provides an article and an ellen show of people's stories of the struggles that follow their foreign name. %0ahttps://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/diversity-inclusion/483720-the-struggle-of-growing-up-in-america-with-a-non%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210227-210010-317700#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)
