diff:1614459609:1614448585:=69,82d68%0a%3c #foxbegin 210227-210010-317700#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!difficulty in pronouncing foreign names %0a%3c -> - kyuwonW%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I also have a similar experience in having many American English speakers be confused with the correct pronunciation of my name. Being tired of people asking repetitively what my name is wherever I went, I got myself an English name at first. But I really didn't like this because every time I told people my English name, it felt like I was giving a fake name, like when ordering coffee from Starbucks. Therefore, I found a simple way of explaining my real name with letters that are used by English speakers, which is saying "Kyuwon = q1". By converting my name into an alphabet and a number, now I can just easily introduce my name to anyone and didn't have to use the English name. %0a%3c %0a%3c Name constitutes of one's identity, so repetitively mispronouncing one's name may seem rude. But it is definitely hard for people to pronounce sounds that aren't in their native language, like the front rounded vowel ü. These technical differences in language do create barriers between people even though they are speaking the same language. It would actually be hard to narrow this technical gap. However, with increasing awareness of diversity every day, people are more willing to accept diverse dialects, tones, and pronunciations without stereotypes. Now in universities, workplaces, and social groups, people attempt to pronounce each other's names correctly until success. These efforts of respecting diversity and each other's language would be a way to solve problems occurring from these barriers. %0a%3c %0a%3c The below link provides an article and an ellen show of people's stories of the struggles that follow their foreign name. %0a%3c https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/diversity-inclusion/483720-the-struggle-of-growing-up-in-america-with-a-non%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210227-210010-317700#%0a
